Looking out the window of the shoebox I rent in downtown Fayetteville, I wonder: "Who on Earth can afford more than a shoebox in downtown Fayetteville?" I get it, though. The city is great, and it has a long and rich history. Maybe someday I'll have a chance of even owning a shoebox in Fayetteville!

A similar question was posed by a team of Bostonites, who wanted to know if the city's renters had a chance of becoming the city's "owners." They used property and assessor data to build key insights in hopes of answering the question. I'd like to do something similar. So I ask: Who owns what in this city?

  • Is the city's ownership well-divided? Or do a handful of entities own most of the property?
  • How common is single property-ownership?
  • Do multi-parcel owning entities have a pattern to their ownership? Is it concentrated or spread out?

    • The data provided by the city, although very good, (Link) does not include a dataset containing both land and ownership records. In fact, parcel ownership data is not made available for download anywhere. So I ended up sending many GET requests -- for 2000 items each -- netting 66,000 parcel / ownership objects to map to the publicly available geospatial data.

First we import some essential modules.

In [ ]:
import os
import json
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd

The data connecting parcels to owners is spread out among many json files. We'll loop through them and combine them into a single, clean dataframe.

In [ ]:
# set dir to parcel data
directory = './parcels'
 
# init empty dataframe
df = pd.DataFrame()

# loop through parcel data files and add them to our main data frame
for filename in os.listdir(directory):
    filepath = os.path.join(directory, filename)
    f = open(filepath)
    # load file json
    data = json.load(f)
    # make new dataframe from 'features' of json
    datFrame = pd.DataFrame()
    datSeries = pd.Series(data['features'])

    for index, row in datSeries.iteritems():
        attr = row['attributes']
        datFrame = datFrame.append(attr, ignore_index=True)

    df = df.append(datFrame)

We'll then save the data so we can use it later or share it easily.

In [ ]:
# our indexes went from 0 - 1999, repeating ~ 34 times
# reset them to start at 0
df = df.reset_index(drop=True)
# save data to disk
df.to_pickle('./parcels.pkl')
df.to_csv('./parcels.csv')

We'd like to connect this ownership data to a geodatabase for visual analysis. We start by loading the geodatabase file.

Lets add our new ownership data to the geodatabase.

In [ ]:
# get just owners with their parcel ids
owners = df[['PARCELID', 'OWNERNME1']].rename(columns={'PARCELID': 'PIN', 'OWNERNME1': 'Owner'})

fay = fay.merge(owners, on='PIN')
fay = fay[['PIN', 'Owner', 'Shape_Length', 'Shape_Area', 'geometry']]
# save for the public good
fay.to_file('owners.geojson', driver='GeoJSON')
In [ ]:
fay = gpd.read_file('owners.geojson')

Now we can ask some interesting questions. For example: Who owns the most parcels?

In [ ]:
# get number of properties owned by each
oc = fay['Owner'].value_counts()

# plot owners with more than 40 properties
oc.sort_values(ascending = False).head(20).plot(kind='barh', title="Fayetteville's Top 20 Landowning Entities, By # of Parcels", figsize=(10,5))

So, it seems that the City of Fayetteville and the University have the Lion's share of parcel ownership.

The University's Land Grab has persisted for a century and a half! We can plot it alongside the City's ownership:

In [ ]:
poi = fay[(fay['Owner'] == 'UNIVERSITY OF ARKANSAS') | (fay['Owner'] == 'CITY OF FAYETTEVILLE')]
fbp = fay.plot(figsize=(15, 15), color="lightgray")
poi.plot(ax=fbp, column='Owner', categorical=True, legend=True).set_axis_off()

And we can quantify this in terms of area, too:

In [ ]:
grouped = fay.groupby(by="Owner").sum()
# Percentage of land owned by the university
uofaArea = grouped[grouped.index == 'UNIVERSITY OF ARKANSAS']['Shape_Area'] / grouped['Shape_Area'].sum()

# Percentage of land owned by the city
cityArea = grouped[grouped.index == 'CITY OF FAYETTEVILLE']['Shape_Area'] / grouped['Shape_Area'].sum()

print(uofaArea[0] + cityArea[0])
print(uofaArea[0])
print(cityArea[0])

0.1764097428659791
0.04302149600202495
0.13338824686395415

By area, the University owns 4.3% of Fayetteville parcels, and combines with the city's 13.3% for a total ~17.6%. This makes sense, as the University plays perhaps the central role in the city's economy.

But are there any other big fish? We can take the top 'n' landowners that are not the City, School District, or University, and evaluate them as well.

In [ ]:
n = 5
topn = grouped[grouped.index.isin(['UNIVERSITY OF ARKANSAS', 'CITY OF FAYETTEVILLE', 'FAYETTEVILLE SCHOOL DISTRICT # 1']) == False]
topn = topn.sort_values('Shape_Area', ascending = False).head(n)
names = []
for index, row in topn.iterrows():
    names.append(index)

poi = fay[(fay['Owner'].isin(names))]
fbp = fay.plot(figsize=(15, 15), color="lightgray")
poi.plot(ax=fbp, column='Owner', cmap='Set1', categorical=True, legend=True).set_axis_off()

Nothing super unexpected here. Other large-area landowners include the mall, some farms... all mostly on the outskirts of town. If we sort by number of parcels owned, (rather than area) maybe we can find some larger players, perhaps downtown?

In [ ]:
topn = oc[oc.index.isin(['UNIVERSITY OF ARKANSAS', 'CITY OF FAYETTEVILLE', 'FAYETTEVILLE SCHOOL DISTRICT # 1']) == False].head(n)
names = []
for index, row in topn.iteritems():

poi.plot(ax=fbp, column='Owner', cmap='rainbow', categorical=True, legend=True).set_axis_off()

Even less interesting. While some of these entities own 100+ parcels, they're hard to even make out, especially compared to the University. They're mostly residential, and none of them are downtown! So what does this mean? Is Fayetteville well-divided in terms of ownership? Maybe not. So far we've only looked at parcel ownership by number and area.

Perhaps a much more important metric is parcel ownership by value. ($$$) It could be that the largest entities are simply the ones with one or two key high-value properties.

This data exists, but is not available for bulk download. Assessed Value Per Acre, Interactive Map
